By the formula for the inradius,
\[r_a = \frac{K}{s - a},\]where $K$ is the area of the triangle, and $s$ is the semiperimeter.  Similarly,
\begin{align*}
r_b &= \frac{K}{s - b}, \\
r_c &= \frac{K}{s - c}.
\end{align*}Hence,
\[\frac{1}{r_a} = \frac{s - a}{K},\]and similarly,
\begin{align*}
\frac{1}{r_b} &= \frac{s - b}{K}, \\
\frac{1}{r_c} &= \frac{s - c}{K}.
\end{align*}Then
\[\frac{1}{r_a} + \frac{1}{r_b} + \frac{1}{r_c} = \frac{3s - (a + b + c)}{K}.\]Since $a + b + c$ is the perimeter of the triangle, $3s - (a + b + c) = s,$ so
\[\frac{1}{r_a} + \frac{1}{r_b} + \frac{1}{r_c} = \frac{1}{r}.\]We want to compute $r.$  We have that
\begin{align*}
\frac{1}{r} &= \frac{1}{a} + \frac{1}{b} + \frac{1}{c} + 2 \sqrt{\frac{1}{ab} + \frac{1}{ac} + \frac{1}{bc}} \\
&= \frac{1}{4} + \frac{1}{9} + \frac{1}{36} + 2 \sqrt{\frac{1}{4 \cdot 9} + \frac{1}{4 \cdot 36} + \frac{1}{9 \cdot 36}} \\
&= \frac{25}{252} + \frac{1}{6} \sqrt{\frac{35}{3}}.
\end{align*}Thus, $r = \boxed{\frac{252}{25} - \frac{1}{6} \sqrt{\frac{35}{3}}}.$

